<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="inc-postmortem-auto-draft-no-publish">
  <metadata>
    <tier>geek</tier>
    <group>sdlc-ai</group>
    <domain>sdlc-ai</domain>
    <summary>LLM agent drafts postmortem from structured signals into a fixed blameless template; humans edit and publish. Agent must never auto-publish or invent facts beyond the signal set.</summary>
    <category>inc</category>
    <difficulty>advanced</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-30</created>
    <tags>
      <tag>postmortem</tag>
      <tag>incident-response</tag>
      <tag>auto-draft</tag>
      <tag>blameless</tag>
      <tag>hypothesis-marking</tag>
    </tags>
    <tools>
      <tool>claude-code</tool>
    </tools>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>Postmortem Auto-Draft, Never Auto-Publish</title>

    <summary>When an incident is resolved, an LLM agent (Rootly, incident.io, FireHydrant pattern) drafts the postmortem from structured signals — Slack channel transcript, alert + deploy timeline, ChatOps /incident actionitem calls, linked PRs — into a fixed template (Summary / Timeline / Impact / Root Cause Hypothesis / Contributing Factors / Action Items) with tone=blameless. The draft lands as a non-published document assigned to the incident commander; humans edit, accept the root-cause framing, and publish. The agent must never auto-publish, never invent facts beyond the structured signal set, and must mark every speculative claim (hypothesis).</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Postmortems get skipped because writing the timeline is the painful 80% of the work; auto-drafting that 80% turns "we never wrote it up" into "we edited a draft in 30 minutes" — Rootly published a 5x throughput improvement with this exact split. But auto-publishing is the failure mode that kills trust: an LLM that picks the wrong root cause and posts it to the org-wide doc destroys the postmortem's value as a learning artifact and exposes legal risk in regulated incidents. Forcing a human-publish step keeps the speed without the misattribution. Marking hypotheses inline preserves the difference between "the deploy correlates with the alert" (fact) and "the deploy caused the outage" (hypothesis under review).</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Teams that currently skip postmortems because writing them is painful.</item>
        <item>Incident-management tools with an autodraft API (Rootly, incident.io, FireHydrant, PagerDuty) or a custom pipeline over Slack + alert + deploy data.</item>
        <item>Engineering cultures that have already adopted blameless postmortem norms.</item>
        <item>Regulated environments where a fast, accurate first-draft helps meet 72-hour reporting windows (EU NIS2, SOC2 incident reporting).</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Highly regulated incidents (legal, safety, financial) where every sentence must be authored by a human from scratch.</item>
        <item>Tiny teams (5 or fewer engineers) where the human writes faster than they can review an LLM draft.</item>
        <item>Teams without a structured timeline source (no Slack channel per incident, no alerts, no deploy log) — the agent will hallucinate without grounding.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="no-auto-publish-rule">
      <p>The drafting workflow MUST land the postmortem in status=draft with a single assignee (the incident commander). The publish API key MUST NOT be in the agent's credential set. Every claim that is not a direct quote from a signal source MUST be tagged (hypothesis) and lives only in the Root Cause Hypothesis and Contributing Factors sections.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>The postmortem agent MUST create the document with status=draft and assignee=incident_commander; MUST NOT possess credentials capable of publishing; MUST mark every non-direct-quote claim as (hypothesis); and MUST refuse to fill the Root Cause field — only Root Cause Hypothesis is agent-writable.</statement>
        <rationale>Auto-publish is the failure mode that destroys the postmortem's purpose: a wrong root cause posted to the org doc becomes the "official" narrative, distorting future decisions. Splitting "Hypothesis" from "Root Cause" preserves the human's authority over the canonical learning.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Rootly workflow with auto_publish false">
        <code lang="yaml"><![CDATA[
# Rootly workflow: on incident_resolved
trigger: incident.status == resolved
actions:
- generate_postmortem:
    template: blameless-v3
    sections: [summary, timeline, impact, root_cause_hypothesis,
               contributing_factors, action_items]
    tone: blameless
    auto_publish: false               # human review required
    assignee: incident_commander
    hypothesis_marker: "(hypothesis)"
        ]]></code>
        <note>Draft only; commander reviews and publishes. No agent credential for the publish endpoint.</note>
      </example>

      <example type="bad" title="Auto-publish with root_cause field">
        <code lang="yaml"><![CDATA[
- generate_postmortem:
    auto_publish: true
    sections: [summary, timeline, root_cause]   # NB: not "hypothesis"
        ]]></code>
        <note>Wrong root cause goes live to the company; engineers cite it for months before someone re-reads.</note>
      </example>

      <antipattern>
        <description>"Auto-publish if confidence &gt; 0.9" thresholds.</description>
        <reason>LLM confidence is uncalibrated for novel incidents; the model is most confident when the situation looks like training data, which is exactly when the surface analogy is misleading.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <templates>
        <template path="templates/postmortem-template.md" purpose="Six-section blameless template."/>
        <template path="templates/draft_postmortem_prompt.txt" purpose="Prompt fragment that enforces no-publish, hypothesis tagging, and citation format."/>
      </templates>

      <see-also>
        <link href="https://rootly.com/sre/ai-generated-postmortems-transform-outage-data-fast"/>
        <link href="https://incident.io/blog/5-best-ai-powered-incident-management-platforms-2026"/>
      </see-also>
    </section>

    <section name="grounded-timeline-only">
      <p>The drafting agent receives only a closed signal set: slack_messages[] (with ts + author), alerts[] (with fired_at + alert_id), deploys[] (with sha + service + ts), action_items[] (from /incident actionitem invocations), linked_prs[]. Each timeline line in the draft MUST cite at least one source by ID. Lines with no citation are invalid; lines paraphrasing a Slack message must include the message link.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Every entry in the postmortem Timeline section MUST end with a bracketed citation list referencing at least one signal ID ([slack:T123/p98...], [alert:HighDBLatency@14:02], [deploy:abc123]). The agent MUST refuse to emit timeline lines without a citation, and MUST NOT cite signals outside the supplied closed set.</statement>
        <rationale>Hallucinated timeline entries are the most damaging output of an LLM-drafted postmortem because timestamps look authoritative. Forcing a citation per line makes hallucinations syntactically detectable: a non-existent ID fails a post-draft validator before the human ever reads it.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Timeline with citation per line">
        <code lang="markdown"><![CDATA[
## Timeline (UTC)

- 14:02 deploy `abc123` reduced pool size 20 → 5 [deploy:abc123]
- 14:04 alert `HighDBLatency` fired (p99 = 1.2s) [alert:HighDBLatency@14:04]
- 14:06 @alice posted "pool exhausted?" [slack:T123/p9806120]
- 14:11 manual revert merged [pr:#4581][slack:T123/p9806840]
        ]]></code>
        <note>Every line is independently auditable; a validator can resolve every citation.</note>
      </example>

      <example type="bad" title="Uncited vague timeline">
        <code lang="markdown"><![CDATA[
- 14:02 a recent change shrank the connection pool
- around 14:05 the database started timing out
- shortly after, the team noticed and rolled back
        ]]></code>
        <note>No citations, vague timestamps, paraphrased intent. Nothing prevents the model from inventing the second line.</note>
      </example>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Allowing the agent to cite a "general knowledge" source like "AWS docs" for a specific incident timeline.</description>
        <reason>The signal set is the universe of truth for one incident; an outside reference smuggles assumptions about what happened from training data, not from the actual outage.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <see-also>
        <link href="https://rootly.com/sre/rootlys-timeline-powers-clear-postmortem-insights"/>
        <link href="https://firehydrant.com/ai/"/>
      </see-also>
    </section>

  </content>
</methodology>
